Second up is the Hidden Hybrid IWB holster (pictured bottom left), which sells new for $60, will throw it in for $40.  Last up is the Glocktech MIC holster (pictured top left), which sells new for $20, will throw it in for $10.  Anyone who carries knows that you usually end up with a whole bunch of holsters before you find one you really like.  Personally, the N82 Tactical turned out to be what I prefer, as it is the most comfortable IWB holster I have owned.  The MIC holster also came in very handy for those times I didn't want to mess with a holster and simply wanted to place the gun in a pocket. title: For Sale:  FRAUD! RARE WINCHESTER 70 FEATHERWEIGHT 6.5X55 SWEDE
postcontent:
I have contacted the person claiming to sell this rifle.  Someone sent me texts from a MI number, and someone else called me continuously from a FL number.  The person I talked to over the phone clearly had a non-USA accent, and claimed that he had moved to Minnesota, but that he was calling me from his land-line (a FL landline in MN?).  The person who texted me from the MI number refused to take the rifle to a gun shop so that I could verify the condition.  They also wanted payment through PayPal (PayPal does not allow transaction for firearms, and if you do, they will not offer any buyer's guarantee).  The person texting me also gave me specs of the Leupold scope, stating that the model number is "70 2-pc" which is obviously not a correct model.  They also listed the rifle on Armslist as a semi-auto.

The number of the person who called me is REDACTED
The number of the person who texted me is REDACTED

Please BEWARE!  Do NOT get caught in this scam.  I have reported this to the authorities as fraud.  They most likely stole the pictures from this legitimate blog post... http://www.missouriwhitetails.com/forums/showthread.php?t=170496

Please help stop these scammers... report this to http://www.stopfraud.gov/  The more complaints they get about this particular scam, the more likely they are to find them and stop them!

The original posting from this scam is posted below...

RARE Winchester Model 70 Featherweight Rifle 6.5 x 55. Winchester Model 70 Featherweight Rifle in the incredibly RARE 6.5 x 55 Caliber. It features a 22" barrel, hinged floor plate, magazine holds 4-Rounds plus 1 in chamber, 3-position safety. It has a deep dark gloss blued finish on barrel, receiver and floorplate. This is one of the VERY RARE Winchester Model 70 FeatherWeight Rifles in the 6.5x55 Caliber! Features the Winchester red recoil pad. Made out of a gorgeous piece of walnut, the stock checkering with the graceful uncheckered ribbon in the pattern will make any rifle-lover stop to admire it. The barrel reads: Winchester Model 70 Featherweight 6.5 x 55 mm, Made in New Haven Conn. USA. The 6.5×55mm is a rimless bottlenecked rifle cartridge. The 6.5x55 is one of the great worldwide hunting cartridges. It offers excellent killing power, adequately flat trajectory, and moderate recoil. It is used for harvesting game including reindeer and moose deer and other medium-sized game. Sportsmen who favor the round load the combination of low recoil coupled with the cartridge's inherent accuracy and superb penetrative qualities. Because 6.5 mm (.264") bullets have relatively high ballistic coefficients, the 6.5×55mm has seen huge successes in long range target matches of 328 yd – 1,094 yd. It is rare thing these days when a product actually lives up to the hype of its advertising, but the Winchester Model 70, "The Rifleman's Rifle," has matched and perhaps surpassed the claims made for this fine arm. For more than half a century they have been called "The Rifleman's Rifle" because of its demonstrated performance, accuracy and dependability. The legendary handling and quickness of the Model 70 Featherweight is justly famous among hunters everywhere. This rifle is in beautiful condition with virtually no signs of handling or use. It comes complete with the scope bases and rings already mounted on it. The 6.5 x 55 is truly a versatile cartridge with the added benefit of being an incredibly RARE caliber in the VERY collectible Winchester Model 70 Featherweight. A real gem for the collector or the shooter in an awesome and RARE caliber, they don't come around like this often! A beautiful and rare addition to someone's gun collection.

title: For Sale:  BUFFALO-BARNES LEAD FREE 45-70 MAG. +P 350 GR. TSX-FN (2150 FPS) - 20 ROUND BOX﻿﻿
postcontent:
http://extreme-impact-ammo.com/index.php?l=product_detail&p=307

This is a super powerful 45-70 +P (or magnum) loading. It is externally identical to SAAMI spec. 45-70 ammo, but internally it generates FAR more power and pressure. So, our 45-70 ammo will fit/chamber into any 45-70 firearm. HOWEVER, its use should be limited to firearms that are built to take the +P pressures it generates.

Its use should be limited to the following firearms: All Marlin 1895 (1895 Marlins are simply 336 actions, with a 45-70 barrel screwed on) iterations made since 1972, all Browning 1885 and 1886 copies, Rossi Rio Grande, New England Arms Handi Rifle, T/C Encore, ALL falling block actions made of modern steel such as the Ruger #1 and #3, Shiloh, Christian and Pedersoli Sharps, all Winchester 1886 iterations made since 1915 and all Siamese mauser bolt actions.

This all copper expanding 350gr. TSX-FN long-for-weight bullet will penetrate about as deep as the typical premium 400gr. + lead core partition expanding bullet, yet it gives the benefits of a lighter bullet, which means it recoils less and has flatter trajectories.

We were not able to develop velocities as fast as we’d like because the long-for-weight all copper bullet crowds the limited powder capacity of the 45-70 casing. Still, 1,900+ fps is very fast and is very powerful and for those who like the benefits of the all copper Barnes TSX-FN bullet, it is a worthwhile trade off. As an added benefit for many, this reduced velocity also means significant recoil reduction.

As always, Buffalo Bore uses real world firearms to generate our published velocities. We feel the industry wide duplicitous practice of generating advertised velocities from extra long laboratory barrels is dishonest to the customer as he/she will not be able to duplicate those velocities in the real world, where it matters.

1,931 fps -- Marlin 1895, 22-inch barrel
1,914 fps -- Marlin 1895, 18-inch barrel

Many shooters do not understand why the 45-70 needs very little barrel length to obtain maximum velocities. As evidenced by the above velocities, ANY straight walled (not a bottle neck case such as the 06 or any number of casings that have a shoulder) case that uses relatively fast burning rifle powders, will generate all the velocity possible in barrels much shorter than bottleneck chamberings.
